“Playing music is the best feeling in the world. As long as I can do that, I’ll be happy.” — Jason Barnes

Jason Barnes (@cybrnetx), a drummer and composer from Atlanta, lost his lower right arm after an electrical accident in 2012. Determined to continue pursuing music, Jason worked with a group of Georgia Tech researchers to create a custom, TensorFlow-powered drumming arm that lets him drum almost as naturally as with his own arm.

Meet Matthew. As someone who was born deaf, he usually relies on video chat and lip-reading to communicate with his son. But by using Live Caption* on his Google Pixel, Matthew made a phone call to his son for the first time in his life. #TrueStories

*English only. Available only on Pixel 2 or newer phones and select other Android phones. Accuracy of Live Caption depends on the quality and clarity of the audio source. Not applicable to music and not available on all media apps. See https://g.co/help/livecaption.

node.text: Today's #GoogleDoodle celebrates swing dancing and the Savoy Ballroom in Harlem, NY. This iconic Swing Era ballroom made history as one of the first racially integrated public spaces in the U.S. when it opened its doors in 1926. Known as the “Home of Happy Feet,” the Savoy Ballroom is also where people first danced iconic dances like the Lindy Hop and the Mambo. Go behind the scenes of the making of today's Doodle and then (Lindy) hop on over to our homepage to test out your own swing dance moves in our multiplayer game.

node.title: Behind the Doodle: Celebrating Swing Dancing and the Savoy Ballroom

node.text:
“Khipus,” which means “knots” in the Quechua language, are the colorful, intricate cords made by the Incas and Waris, South America's oldest empires. Approximately 85% of khipus contain knots representing numbers, while the remaining 15% are believed to be encoding biographies, histories and poetry without written words on paper or stone. Researchers are still working to decipher the meanings of these coded messages.

This week, @MuseoDeArteLima and @GoogleArtsCulture launched an online exhibition — The Khipu Keepers — so people from across the world can learn more about the legacy of the Inca civilization. Explore for yourself at g.co/khipus, or by tapping the link in our bio.

node.text:
If you give a designer cutting-edge technologies and platforms… 
they’re gonna want to explore the boundaries of ambient computing. 

And if they explore the boundaries of ambient computing… 
they’re gonna imagine new ways to integrate computing into our everyday lives — like in the clothes we wear.

On July 7 at Paris Haute Couture Week, @GoogleATAP unveiled the first installment of “Ambient Experiments with Google ATAP,” designed by @claradaguin using technology and software developed by the #JacquardbyGoogle team. Swipe through the photos to see the creations, and tap the link in bio to learn more.

Photographs by @leo_cannone

Her dress is a bright white illuminated pinwheel of fabric on her front; her back is mostly bare.
